
Homework #1

1.) Function in C lanaguage: This was compiled and confirmed working with MBED LPC1768 and application board. 
    The main program runs the test vectors inputs from 0 to 7 and displays the gray code in the LCD diplay of the app. board.
    (Pls. see pictures of app. board running the program in the suppporting pdf file).
    
    Below table summarizes the results generated by the C functions decode1,2, and 3:
    
    Dec (input)    Gray Code (Output)
     0                  000
     1                  001  
     2                  011 
     3                  010
     4                  110
     5                  111
     6                  101
     7                  111 
     
     
Here is the program listing:

#include "mbed.h"
#include "C12832.h"


C12832 lcd(p5, p7, p6, p8, p11);

/*Functions to encode Decimal 0 to 7 to Gray Code by Look-up Table*/ 
int decode1 (int a)

{
    int c[1];
    c[1]=0;
    switch(a) {
                    case 0:
                         c[1]=0;
                         break;
                    case 1:
                         c[1]=1;
                         break;
                    case 2:
                         c[1]=1;
                         break;
                    case 3:
                         c[1]=0;
                         break;
                    case 4:
                         c[1]=0;
                         break;
                    case 5:
                         c[1]=1;
                         break;
                    case 6:
                         c[1]=1;
                         break;
                    case 7:
                         c[1]=0;
                         break;

                }
    return c[1];

}

int decode2 (int a)

{
    int c[1];
    c[1]=0;
    switch(a) {
                    case 0:
                         c[1]=0;
                         break;
                    case 1:
                         c[1]=0;
                         break;
                    case 2:
                         c[1]=1;
                         break;
                    case 3:
                         c[1]=1;
                         break;
                    case 4:
                         c[1]=1;
                         break;
                    case 5:
                         c[1]=1;
                         break;
                    case 6:
                         c[1]=0;
                         break;
                    case 7:
                         c[1]=0;
                         break;

                }
    return c[1];

}

int decode3 (int a)

{
    int c[1];
    c[1]=0;
    switch(a) {
                    case 0:
                         c[1]=0;
                         break;
                    case 1:
                         c[1]=0;
                         break;
                    case 2:
                         c[1]=0;
                         break;
                    case 3:
                         c[1]=0;
                         break;
                    case 4:
                         c[1]=1;
                         break;
                    case 5:
                         c[1]=1;
                         break;
                    case 6:
                         c[1]=1;
                         break;
                    case 7:
                         c[1]=1;
                         break;

                }
    return c[1];

}

/* Main Calling the function decode1,2,3 */
int main()
{
   
    int j=0;
    int z[4];
    lcd.cls();
    lcd.locate(0,3);
    lcd.printf("Decimal to Gray Code");

    while(1) {   // this is the third thread
        lcd.locate(0,15);
        z[1] = decode1 (j);
        z[2] = decode2 (j);
        z[3] = decode3 (j); 
        lcd.printf("Decimal:%i Gray Code:%i%i%i",j,z[3],z[2],z[1]);
        j++;
        if (j==8){
            j=0;
            }
        wait(1.0);
    }
}

Kindly refer to the  supporting pdf file of this assignment for te pictures of the MBED board running this program.



2.) Hardware discovery project: Parallax USB two channel Oscilloscope (2006 model).
    Kindly refer to the supporting pdf file of this assignment for the board pictures.

Microcontroller:  Parallax SX48DB
                  8 bit RISC microcontroller
                  Harvard architecture
                  Clock Frequency up to 75Mhz
                  262 Bytes SRAM
                  4K words EEPROM (Flash)
                  No mention of cache memory
                  Operating voltage: 3.0VDC to 5.5VDC
                  One 8 bit RTCC with programmable 8 bit prescaler
                  36 bi-directional I/O pins
                    
The SX48DB mincroncontroler uses its I/O pins to communicate with the IC FT32RL for the USB interface.
The microcontroller also uses its I/O pins to read analog data from the ADC LTC2286 for the two channel oscilloscope inputs.
There are 4 header pins near the edge of the board for test and programming function of the manufacturer. 
